 JAPAN, Feb 8 (bdnews24.com/Reuters)-- Toyota shares edge lower despite an apology by the automaker's president, as a Japanese recall for the top-selling Prius Hybrid looms. Toyota shares edged lower on Monday despite an apology by the automaker's president, as a Japanese recall for the top-selling Prius hybrid loomed. Akio Toyoda made a public apology for the recall of some 8 million vehicles around the world on Friday, saying the Japanese company would bring in outside experts to review quality controls. Japanese dealers say the recall is set to grow larger with domestic models of the latest Prius added to fix a braking software glitch. The world No.1 automaker is also considering a recall of its Sai and Lexus hybrid models that use the same brake system as the Prius, Japanese media reported. The new Prius was a top seller last year, helping to lead Toyota back from billions of dollars in losses in the wake of the global financial crisis. The wave of new problems over the last two weeks has shrunk Toyota's market value by 20 percent and is expected to cost the 77-year-old company at least $2 billion. Toyota shares rose early in the day but could not keep gains, and are now some 60 percent below February 2007 lev
